# **Response to Fast Fish – “AI Store-Product Matching” Project**

 **Date:** 2 July 2025 | **Prepared by:** Web3 Research / Aisle8 (Andy Keh & Team)

---

### **1 Executive Summary**

Fast Fish’s latest brief shifts success from SPU-level replenishment to *strategic* style-width planning at the **Store Group × Style Tags** level, measured by **sell-through uplift**.  
 Our platform already clusters stores and scores SPUs; we will now add a **Style-Count Optimizer** plus explainability and auto-refresh to deliver:

| Stage | Purpose | Key Output |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| 1 | Strategic decision layer | AI-generated table of optimal style counts, with business rationale & benefit projection |
| 2 | Store-level execution (activated after Stage 1 sign-off) | Add/Remove SPU list derived from Stage 1 targets |

### **1 执行摘要**

Fast Fish 的最新简报将成功从 SPU 级补货转移到*战略*风格宽度规划**商店组 × 风格标签**水平，通过测量**销售量提升**。  
我们的平台已经对商店进行了集群化并对 SPU 进行了评分；我们现在将添加一个**样式计数优化器**加上可解释性和自动刷新功能，可提供：

| 阶段 | 目的 | 按键输出 |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| 1 | 战略决策层 | 人工智能生成的最佳款式数量表，包含商业原理和收益预测 |
| 2 | 商店级执行（第一阶段签字后激活） | 添加/删除来自第 1 阶段目标的 SPU 列表 |

### **2 Direct Mapping – Your Requirements → Our Commitments**

| \# | Fast Fish Requirement | Our Implementation |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| 1 | **Granularity** – one row per *Store Group × Style Tags × half-month*; no SPU data in Stage 1 | Strategic Style-Count Table (fields: Year, Month, Period, Store Group, \[Tags\], Target SPU Qty) |
| 2 | **Target metric** – “optimal number of SPU Codes” | Style-Count Optimizer calculates *Target SPU Qty* |
| 3 | **Goal-oriented** – maximize sell-through / profit | Loss function & validation centred on projected sell-through % uplift |
| 4 | **Dynamic & explainable** – auto-refresh, business-language rationale | Regular re-compute; columns *Data-Based Rationale* and *Expected Benefit Improvement* per row |
| 5 | **Two-stage path** – strategy first, execution second | Stage 1 delivers targets; Stage 2 (non-urgent) fills gaps via existing SPU recommender |

STAGE 1 FOCUS 

**Stage 1 Playbook – “Strategic Style-Count Table” (Only)**

*Goal: deliver the optimal **Target SPU Qty** per **Cluster / Store × Sub-Category** with a clear, business-readable rationale driven by Sell-Through Rate.*

---

## **1 North-Star KPI**

| KPI | Why it matters | How it’s used in the model |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **Sell-Through Rate (%) uplift** | Fast Fish’s principal measure of assortment success | Loss-function to choose Target SPU Qty that maximises projected ST% |

*Revenue, GM$, turns are monitored but **not** optimised.*

---

## **2 Data Lenses & Feature Store**

| Lens | Must-have fields | Example features (auto-logged for rationale) |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **Store** | floor space, fixtures, traffic, geo-cluster | Capacity facings, traffic index, cluster label |
| **Customer** | loyalty/POS mix → gender, age, style-index | **% Women / % Men**, **% Trendy / % Basic**, basket size |
| **Environmental** | daily temp, humidity, holiday flags | 14-day temp avg, rainfall anomaly, holiday proximity |
| **Fashion Trends** | Weibo/Xiaohongshu index per sub-cat | Trend momentum (WoW / YoY) |

All feeds land in a **versioned Feature Store** (Snowflake Delta). Snapshots are preserved so the history appears in explanations (“last summer ST % \= 48”).

---

## **3 Modelling & Optimisation Pipeline**

1. **Demand Predictor** – gradient-boosted tree (LightGBM); target \= sell-through %.

2. **Sell-Through Simulator** – converts ST% to sales/GM$ for business visibility.

3. **Style-Count Optimiser** – loops style\_qty \= 1…N; picks qty with **max ST% uplift** under capacity.

4. **Explainability Layer** – SHAP → bullet narrative tied to the 4 data lenses.

**Cycle time:** \< 45 min; re-runs nightly or on new data trigger.

---

## **4 Output Spec – *Strategic Style-Count Table***

| Column | Example | Description / Rationale hook |
| ----- | ----- | ----- |
| Year | 2025 | Calendar year |
| Month | 08 | Numeric month |
| Period (A/B) | A | 1–15 \= A; 16-EoM \= B |
| Cluster Name | East-Urban | Geo-behaviour cluster |
| Store ID *(opt.)* | BJ0123 | (omit for cluster-only view) |
| Sub-Category Tags | \[Men, Cargo, Summer\] | Full tag list |
| **Current SPU Qty** | 4 | Distinct SPUs now carried |
| **Target SPU Qty** | 6 | Optimiser result |
| ΔQty | \+2 | Target – Current |
| **Customer Mix** | 62 % M / 38 % F; 47 % trendy | Auto-filled from features |
| Trend Momentum | \+28 % WoW | Fashion-trend signal |
| Temp 14d Avg | 30 °C | Environmental signal |
| Historical ST% (Last Y) | 48 % | Context baseline |
| **Data-Based Rationale** | “62 % male \+ cargo trend ↑ \+ hot weather” | Single field with bullet narrative (top-3 drivers) |
| **Expected ST Uplift** | \+11 pp | Projection from simulator |

*Business team sees “Current vs Target”, the four data lenses, and the projected benefit on one line.*

---

## **5 Explainability Template (per row)**

**Why 6 styles?**  
 • **Customer:** 62 % male, 47 % trendy shoppers → preference for cargo pants  
 • **Trend:** Cargo index **\+28 %** week-over-week  
 • **Environment:** Forecast avg **30 °C** next 14 days (light fabrics sell)  
 • **History:** Last Aug ST \= 48 % with 4 styles; simulation shows **\+11 pp** ST if assortment widens to 6 within capacity 8 facings.
